06636nam a22010335i 9783110197709DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20082007gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013955547  a97831101977097 a10.1515/97831101977092doi  a(DE-B1597)32242  a(OCoLC)853254655  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP165b.C67 2006eb 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a415.028522200aCorpora in Cognitive Linguistics :bCorpus-Based Approaches to Syntax and Lexis /ced. by Anatol Stefanowitsch, Stefan Th. Gries. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2008] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMouton Select0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCognitive Linguistics, the branch of linguistics that tries to "make one's account of human language accord with what is generally known about the mind and the brain," has become one of the most flourishing fields of contemporary linguistics. The chapters address many classic topics of Cognitive Linguistics. These topics include studies on the semantics of specific words (including polysemy and synonymy) as well as semantic characteristics of particular syntactic patterns / constructions (including constructional synonymy and the schematicity of constructions), the analysis of causatives, transitivity, and image-schematic aspects of posture verbs. The key characteristic of this volume is that all papers adopt the methodological perspective of Corpus Linguistics, the rapidly evolving branch of linguistics based on the computerized analysis of language used in authentic settings. Thus, the contributions do not only all provide various new insights in their respective fields, they also introduce new data as well as new corpus-based and quantitative methods of analysis. On the basis of their findings, the authors discuss both theoretical implications going well beyond the singular topics of the studies and show how the discipline of Cognitive Linguistics can benefit from the rigorous analysis of naturally-occurring language. The languages which are investigated are English, German, Dutch, and Russian, and the data come from a variety of different corpora. As such, the present volume will be of interest to a wide range of scholars with many different foci and interests and should pave the way for further integration of usage-based techniques of analysis within this exciting paradigm.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aCognitive grammarxData processing. 0aGrammaire cognitivexInformatique. 4aDatenanalyse. 4aKognitive Linguistik. 4aKorpora. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aCognitive linguistics.  acorpora.  adata analysis.1 aDivjak, Dagmar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilquin, Gaëtanelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGries, Stefan Th., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGries, Stefan Th., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHampe, Beate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHollmann, Willem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLemmens, Maarten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewman, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRice, Sally, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchönefeld, Doris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStefanowitsch, Anatol, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWulff, Stefanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle i